## ⚠️ Discrepancies Found

The following inconsistencies, missing relationships, or mismatches were discovered during the comprehensive codebase analysis:

### 1. Serializer–Model Mismatch (`apps.users.serializers`)

> [!WARNING]
> The `AdminUserSerializer` and `UserMeSerializer` reference fields `user_type` and `get_user_type_display` which **do not exist** on the `AdminUser` model. The model uses `role` (not `user_type`). These serializers are **unused** in the current codebase (views use inline dict construction instead), so this is dead code with an incorrect schema reference.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/users/serializers.py` (lines 5, 9, 14)  
**Impact:** Low — serializers are not called from any view, but could cause runtime `AttributeError` if ever used.

---

### 2. Notification `is_read` Is Global, Not Per-User

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `Notification` model has a single `is_read` boolean field with no user FK. The `MarkAllReadView` sets `is_read=True` globally for **all** users. This means if one user marks notifications as read, they are marked read for **everyone**. This is a significant design flaw for a multi-user system.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/notifications/models.py` (line 40), `views.py` (line 22)  
**Expected:** A many-to-many relationship (e.g., `NotificationReadStatus` table with `user_id` + `notification_id`).

---

### 3. `analytics` App is Empty

> [!NOTE]
> The `apps/analytics/` directory exists with `__pycache__` and `migrations/` but has **no models.py, views.py, urls.py, or any functional code**. It is not registered in `INSTALLED_APPS`. All analytics functionality is implemented in `apps.core` instead. This is an orphan directory.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/analytics/`  
**Impact:** None (dead directory), but should be cleaned up.

---

### 4. Duplicate Feedback Mechanisms

> [!NOTE]
> The system has **two separate feedback mechanisms**:
> - `apps.feedback.Feedback` — direct feedback with category, rating, facility/room, and flag fields
> - `apps.core.Rating` + `apps.core.FeedbackFlag` — star ratings with a moderation workflow
> 
> Both serve overlapping purposes. The frontend `FeedbackView.vue` submits to `/api/feedback/` while the Admin panel's `AdminFeedback.vue` manages the `core.Rating` model. There is no clear separation of concerns.

---

### 5. Dean Account Enforcement Not in Code

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The user's requirement states "every department must have its own Dean account." However, the codebase does **not enforce** a one-dean-per-department constraint. Multiple deans can exist for the same department, or a department can have zero deans. There is no unique constraint on `(role='dean', department)` in the model or any validation in the views.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/users/models.py`  
**Expected:** Either a DB-level unique constraint or a view-level validation ensuring exactly one dean per department.

---

### 6. Flask `chatbot.db` Has No Timestamps

> [!NOTE]
> The Flask chatbot's `chat_history` table has no `created_at` timestamp column, making it impossible to query historical chat data by time range. The Django `ai_chat_logs` table does have timestamps, but the Flask service uses its own separate database.

**File:** `chatbot_flask/app.py` (lines 17-22)

---

### 7. Rooms Ownership Filtering Not Enforced at API Level

> [!WARNING]
> The `RoomListView` and `RoomDetailView` use `permissions.IsAuthenticatedOrReadOnly`, which allows **any authenticated admin** to create/edit/delete **any** room. The "manage own department rooms" restriction is only enforced in the **frontend UI** (AdminView conditionally shows the room tab scoped to `auth.department`), not in the backend API. A determined user could bypass the frontend and modify rooms outside their department via direct API calls.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/rooms/views.py`  
**Expected:** A custom permission class that checks `request.user.department` against the room's facility department for non-super-admin users.

---

### 8. Missing `apps` App Configurations

> [!NOTE]
> Several Django apps (`facilities`, `rooms`, `navigation`, `chatbot`, `notifications`, `feedback`) lack proper `apps.py` configuration files with `AppConfig` classes. While Django can auto-discover these, explicit `AppConfig` is best practice for production systems.

---

### 9. Frontend `users` IndexedDB Store References `user_type`

> [!NOTE]
> The frontend IndexedDB schema in `db.js` defines `users: '++id, username, user_type, is_active'` using `user_type` as an index, but the backend model uses `role` (not `user_type`). This is a schema name mismatch between frontend and backend. However, this store is flagged as "Local only" and not synced from the server, so the practical impact is low.

**File:** `frontend/src/services/db.js` (line 41)

---

### 10. `Announcement.archive()` Method Has No API Endpoint

> [!NOTE]
> The `Announcement` model has an `archive()` method and `archived_by`/`archived_at` fields, but there is **no API endpoint** to trigger archiving. It can only be called programmatically. The frontend admin panel has no UI for archiving announcements either.

**File:** `backend_django/apps/announcements/models.py` (lines 111-117), `urls.py`
